HEADWORD: Peregrine
<hw>Per"e*grine</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧r"⟦esl⟧*gr⟦icr⟧n; 277)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>peregrinus</ets>. See
<er>Pilgrim</er>.]</ety> <def>Foreign; not native; extrinsic or from
without; exotic.</def> <altsp>[Spelt also <asp>pelegrine</asp>.]</altsp>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Peregrine</xex> and preternatural heat.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Peregrine falcon</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
courageous and swift falcon (<spn>Falco peregrinus</spn>), remarkable
for its wide distribution over all the continents. The adult plumage is
dark bluish ash on the back, nearly black on the head and cheeks, white
beneath, barred with black below the throat. Called also
<altname>peregrine hawk</altname>, <altname>duck hawk</altname>,
<altname>game hawk</altname>, and <altname>great-footed
hawk</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1065 --></p>

<p><ent>Peregrine</ent>⟦br⟧

